&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to go down in flames&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;has roots in aerial combat, where a plane shot down might literally go down in flames. This vivid imagery is a metaphor for spectacular failure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In contemporary use, this idiom has transcended its military origins. Today, it is applied to a wide range of failures, not just in battles but in business, personal projects, relationships, and more. It suggests not just failure, but a failure that is dramatic and visible to others.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

